==English==
[[File:Palomena prasina, Budapest, Hungary - 20101021.jpg|thumb|A [[w:green shield bug|green shield bug]] (''Palomena prasina'') in [[w:Budapest|Budapest]], [[w:Hungary|Hungary]]. It is an [[insect]] of the [[order]] [[Hemiptera]], and so is one of the "true bugs".]]

===Etymology===
First attested in this form around 1620 (referring to a [[bedbug]]), from earlier {{m|en|bugge||beetle}}, a conflation of two words:
# {{der|en|enm|bugge||scarecrow, hobgoblin}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*bugja-||swollen up, thick}} (compare {{cog|no|bugge||big man}}, dialectal Low German {{m|nds|Bögge||goblin”, “snot}}
# {{der|en|enm|budde||beetle}}, from Old English {{m|ang|budda}} (see {{m|ang|scearnbudda||dung beetle}}), from {{der|en|gem-pro|*buddô}}, {{m|gem-pro|*buzdô}} (compare {{cog|nds|Budde||louse, grub}}, {{cog|no|budda||newborn domestic animal}}). More at {{l|en|bud}}.
The term is used to refer to technical errors and problems at least as early as the 19th century, predating the commonly known story of a moth being caught in a computer.

